---
import DocsLayout from '../../../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import CodeBlock from '../../../../../components/CodeBlock.astro';
import Callout from '../../../../../components/Callout.astro';
---

<DocsLayout title="Design" description="Create the design spec for Vinyl Vault Records.">
  <h1 class="mb-6">Design</h1>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Same process as P3 — client preferences, prompt, template, review, mockup, iterate. You know the steps. The emphasis here is on what's specific to a record store design.</p>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Marcus's visual preferences</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">You follow up with Marcus about the look and feel. He flips through a crate of records while he talks:</p>

  <Callout variant="client">
    <p>"Think classic record shop. Black, white, pops of colour from album art. The records ARE the design — they're colourful enough. I like bold typography, clean grid layouts. Look at Discogs but simpler. Don't make it look like a tech startup."</p>
  </Callout>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">The prompt</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Paste this into Claude along with the design spec template and your PRD:</p>

  <CodeBlock copy>{`Here is a PRD for an online record store:

[Paste your PRD]

And here are the client's visual preferences:

"Think classic record shop. Black, white, pops of colour from album art. The records ARE the design — they're colourful enough. Bold typography, clean grid layouts. Like Discogs but simpler. Not a tech startup look."

Using the following design spec template, generate a complete design specification. Focus on the product card component — album art is the visual centrepiece. Specify exact colour hex values, typography, spacing, responsive behaviour, and how the dark background interacts with album art.

[Paste design template from /templates]`}</CodeBlock>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Review the output</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Same review process as P3, with these specific checks:</p>

  <h3 class="mb-3 mt-6">Contrast on dark backgrounds</h3>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Marcus wants black backgrounds. Dark themes need careful text contrast — white text on dark grey is fine, but light grey text on dark grey might not meet WCAG AA (4.5:1). Paste the hex values into a <a href="https://webaim.org/resources/contrastchecker/">contrast checker</a> and verify.</p>

  <h3 class="mb-3 mt-6">Product grid layout</h3>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Records need to be visual — album art is the hero. The spec should define:</p>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-secondary space-y-2 text-sm mb-6">
    <li><strong class="text-text">Image aspect ratio:</strong> Album covers are square (1:1). Enforce this in the spec.</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Grid columns:</strong> How many per row at each breakpoint?</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Text truncation:</strong> Long artist names and album titles need a defined behaviour.</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Price display:</strong> Currency format, position, size.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3 class="mb-3 mt-6">Mobile considerations</h3>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-8">Cart and checkout on mobile matter — people browse record stores on their phones. The spec should address: product grid on mobile (2 columns, not 1), cart UI on small screens, and checkout flow (Stripe handles the payment UI, but the surrounding page is yours).</p>

  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Use the mockup technique from P3 — paste the PRD and design spec into claude.ai, ask for a React artifact mockup, and iterate. Show Marcus. Does it feel like his shop?</p>

  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">If you have a <a href="https://www.figma.com/">Figma</a> account (free), try pasting your design spec into Claude and asking it to create a Figma-ready component spec. Or use the mockup technique from P1 — paste into claude.ai and ask for a React artifact. Either way, the goal is a visual reference you can show the client before writing code.</p>

  <h3 class="mb-3 mt-6">A note on design tokens</h3>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-8">In larger projects, design specs include design tokens — a JSON file defining colours, spacing, typography, and other values that both designers and developers reference. The design spec you're generating is the human-readable version. From Project 7 onwards, you'll work with formal token files.</p>

  <Callout variant="info">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>Save your design spec as a markdown file.</strong> You'll reference it throughout the project — same as P3.</p>
  </Callout>

  <div class="mt-8 p-6 bg-primary-bg rounded-lg border border-primary/20 text-center">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-2">Next: architecture</h2>
    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Design spec is done. Now plan how it's built.</p>
    <a
      href="/web-dev/projects/4/architecture"
      class="inline-block bg-primary hover:bg-primary-dark text-white font-semibold py-3 px-6 rounded-md transition-colors min-h-[44px]"
    >
      Architecture →
    </a>
  </div>
</DocsLayout>
